# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: alfred-village-new-york
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:alfred-village-new-york/1860-united-states-census] The **1860 United States census** was the eighth census conducted in the United States, starting June 1, 1860, and lasting five months.
[src:alfred-village-new-york/1860-united-states-census] It determined the population of the United States to be 31,443,321 in 33 states and 10 organized territories.
[src:alfred-village-new-york/1860-united-states-census] This was an increase of 35.6 percent over the 23,191,876 persons enumerated during the 1850 census.
[src:alfred-village-new-york/1860-united-states-census] The total population included 3,953,760 slaves.
[src:alfred-village-new-york/1860-united-states-census] By the time the 1860 census returns were ready for tabulation, the nation was sinking into the American Civil War.
[src:alfred-village-new-york/1860-united-states-census] As a result, census superintendent Joseph C.
[src:alfred-village-new-york/1860-united-states-census] Kennedy and his staff produced only an abbreviated set of public reports, without graphic or cartographic representations.
[src:alfred-village-new-york/1860-united-states-census] The statistics did allow the census staff to produce a cartographic display, including preparing maps of Southern states, for Union field commanders.
[src:alfred-village-new-york/1860-united-states-census] These maps displayed militarily vital topics, including the white population, slave population, predominant agricultural products (by county), and rail and post road transportation routes.
[src:alfred-village-new-york/1860-united-states-census] Philadelphia would lose its position as the second-most-populous American city to Chicago in 1890.
[src:alfred-village-new-york/1860-united-states-census] The 1860 census Schedule 1 (Free Inhabitants) was one of two schedules that counted the population of the United States; the other was Schedule 2 (Slave Inhabitants).
[src:alfred-village-new-york/1860-united-states-census] Full documentation for the 1860 population census, including microdata, census forms and enumerator instructions, is available from the Integrated Public Use Microdata Series (IPUMS).
[src:alfred-village-new-york/1860-united-states-census] Aggregate data for small areas, together with compatible cartographic boundary files, can be downloaded from the National Historical Geographic Information System.
[src:alfred-village-new-york/1860-united-states-census] National data reveals that farmers (owners and tenants) made up nearly 10% of utilized occupations.
[src:alfred-village-new-york/1860-united-states-census] Farm laborers (wage workers) represent the next highest percent with 3.2%, followed by general laborers at 3.0%.
[src:alfred-village-new-york/1860-united-states-census] More localized data shows that other occupations were common.
[src:alfred-village-new-york/1860-united-states-census] In the town of Essex, Massachusetts, a large section of the women in the labor force were devoted to shoe-binding, while for men the common occupations were farming and shoe-making.
[src:alfred-village-new-york/1860-united-states-census] This heavy demand of shoe-related labor reinforces the high demand for rigorous physical laborers in the economy, as supported by the data of very large amounts of farm related work as compared to most other labor options.
[src:alfred-village-new-york/1860-united-states-census] IPUMS' data also notes that the share of the population that had been enrolled in school or marked as "Student" stood at 0.2%.
[src:alfred-village-new-york/1860-united-states-census] This demonstrates a small rate of growth, if any, in the proficiency of the human capital of the time—the skill set a worker has to apply to the labor force, which can increase total output through increased efficiency.
[src:alfred-village-new-york/1860-united-states-census] The census of 1860 was the last in which much of Southern wealth was held as slaves—still legally considered property.
[src:alfred-village-new-york/1880-united-states-census] The **1880 United States census**, conducted by the Census Office during June 1880, was the tenth United States census.
[src:alfred-village-new-york/1880-united-states-census] It was the first time that women were permitted to be enumerators.
[src:alfred-village-new-york/1880-united-states-census] The Superintendent of the Census was Francis Amasa Walker.
[src:alfred-village-new-york/1880-united-states-census] This was the first census in which a city—New York City—recorded a population of over one million, and the first census in which the 20 most populated cities all recorded over 100,000 residents.
[src:alfred-village-new-york/1880-united-states-census] Schedule 4 (Social statistics) was the responsibility of experts and special agents, rather than the enumerators.
[src:alfred-village-new-york/1880-united-states-census] The majority of the data came from correspondence with officials of institutions providing care and treatment of certain members of the population.
[src:alfred-village-new-york/1880-united-states-census] Experts and special agents also were employed to collect data on valuation, taxation, and indebtedness; religion and libraries; colleges, academies, and schools; newspapers and periodicals, and wages.
[src:alfred-village-new-york/1880-united-states-census] Full documentation for the 1880 population census, including census forms and enumerator instructions, is available from the Integrated Public Use Microdata Series, which contains microdata.
[src:alfred-village-new-york/1880-united-states-census] The original census enumeration sheets were microfilmed by the Census Bureau; after which the original sheets were transferred to various state archives, libraries, or universities.
[src:alfred-village-new-york/1880-united-states-census] The microfilmed census is available in rolls from the National Archives and Records Administration.
[src:alfred-village-new-york/1880-united-states-census] Several organizations also host images of the microfilmed census online, along which digital indices.
[src:alfred-village-new-york/1880-united-states-census] Microdata from the 1880 population census are freely available through the Integrated Public Use Microdata Series.
[src:alfred-village-new-york/1880-united-states-census] The 1880 census determined the resident population of the United States to be 50,189,209, an increase of 30.2 percent over the 38,555,983 persons enumerated during the 1870 census.
[src:alfred-village-new-york/1880-united-states-census] The mean center of United States population for 1880 was in Boone County, Kentucky.
[src:alfred-village-new-york/1880-united-states-census] The results from the census were used to determine the apportionment for the 48th, 49th, 50th, 51st, and 52nd sessions of the United States Congress.
[src:alfred-village-new-york/1880-united-states-census] The processing of the 1880 census data took so long (eight years) that the Census Bureau contracted Herman Hollerith to design and build a tabulating machine to be used for the next census.
[src:alfred-village-new-york/1880-united-states-census] The 1880 census also led to the discovery of the Alabama paradox.
[src:alfred-village-new-york/1890-united-states-census] The **1890 United States census** was taken beginning June 2, 1890.
[src:alfred-village-new-york/1890-united-states-census] The census determined the resident population of the United States to be 62,979,766, an increase of 25.5 percent over the 50,189,209 persons enumerated during the 1880 census.
[src:alfred-village-new-york/1890-united-states-census] The data reported that the distribution of the population had resulted in the disappearance of the American frontier.
[src:alfred-village-new-york/1890-united-states-census] This was the first census in which a majority of states recorded populations of over one million and the first in which three cities, New York City, Chicago, and Philadelphia, recorded populations of over one million.
[src:alfred-village-new-york/1890-united-states-census] The census also saw Chicago rise in rank to the nation's second-most populous city, a position it would hold until Los Angeles, the 57th-most populous city as of 1890, supplanted it in 1990.
[src:alfred-village-new-york/1890-united-states-census] This was the first U.S. census to use machines to tabulate the collected data.
[src:alfred-village-new-york/1890-united-states-census] Most of the 1890 census materials were destroyed on January 10, 1921, when the Commerce Department building caught fire, and in the subsequent disposal of the remaining damaged records.
[src:alfred-village-new-york/1890-united-states-census] The 1890 census was the first to be compiled using methods invented by Herman Hollerith and was overseen by Superintendents Robert P.
[src:alfred-village-new-york/1890-united-states-census] Data was entered on a machine readable medium (punched cards) and tabulated by machine.
[src:alfred-village-new-york/1890-united-states-census] Changes from the 1880 census included the larger population, the number of data items to be collected from individuals, the Census Bureau headcount, the volume of scheduled publications, and the use of Hollerith's electromechanical tabulators.
[src:alfred-village-new-york/1890-united-states-census] The net effect of these changes was to reduce the time required to process the census from eight years for the 1880 census to six years for the 1890 census.
[src:alfred-village-new-york/1890-united-states-census] The total population of 62,947,714, the family, or *rough*, count, was announced after only six weeks of processing (punched cards were not used for this tabulation).
[src:alfred-village-new-york/1890-united-states-census] The public reaction to this tabulation was disbelief, as it was widely believed that the "right answer" was at least 75,000,000.
[src:alfred-village-new-york/1890-united-states-census] The United States census of 1890 showed a total of 248,253 Native Americans living in the United States, down from 400,764 Native Americans identified in the census of 1850.
[src:alfred-village-new-york/1890-united-states-census] The 1890 census announced that the frontier region of the United States no longer existed, and that the Census Bureau would no longer track the westward migration of the U.S. population.
[src:alfred-village-new-york/1890-united-states-census] In practice, however, said migration can still be tracked by plotting each succeeding census' mean center of United States population.
[src:alfred-village-new-york/1890-united-states-census] By 1890, settlement in the American West had reached sufficient population density that the frontier line had disappeared.
[src:alfred-village-new-york/1890-united-states-census] The original data for the 1890 census is mostly unavailable.
[src:alfred-village-new-york/1890-united-states-census] The population schedules were damaged in a fire in the basement of the U.S.
[src:alfred-village-new-york/1890-united-states-census] Department of Commerce building in Washington, D.C. in 1921.
[src:alfred-village-new-york/1890-united-states-census] Some 25% of the materials were presumed destroyed and another 50% damaged by smoke and water, although the actual damage may have been closer to 15–25%.
[src:alfred-village-new-york/1890-united-states-census] The damage to the records led to an outcry for a permanent National Archives.
[src:alfred-village-new-york/1890-united-states-census] In December 1932, following standard federal record-keeping procedures, the Chief Clerk of the Bureau of the Census sent the Librarian of Congress a list of papers to be destroyed, including the original 1890 census schedules.
[src:alfred-village-new-york/1890-united-states-census] The Librarian was asked by the Bureau to identify any records which should be retained for historical purposes, but the Librarian did not accept the census records.
[src:alfred-village-new-york/1890-united-states-census] Congress authorized destruction of that list of records on February 21, 1933, and the surviving original 1890 census records were destroyed by government order by 1934 or 1935.
[src:alfred-village-new-york/1890-united-states-census] Few sets of microdata from the 1890 census survive.
[src:alfred-village-new-york/1900-united-states-census] The **1900 United States census**, conducted by the Census Office on June 1, 1900, determined the resident population of the United States to be 76,212,168, an increase of 21.01% from the 62,979,766 persons enumerated during the 1890 census.
[src:alfred-village-new-york/1900-united-states-census] It was the last census to be conducted before the founding of the permanent United States Census Bureau.
[src:alfred-village-new-york/1900-united-states-census] The census saw the nation's largest city, New York City, more than double in size due to the consolidation with Brooklyn, becoming in the process the first U.S. city to record a population growth of over three million — Brooklyn was previously the 4th largest city in the United States on its own.
[src:alfred-village-new-york/1900-united-states-census] Oversight of the statistics was by Frederick Howard Wines and Walter F.
[src:alfred-village-new-york/1900-united-states-census] Full documentation for the 1900 census, including census forms and enumerator instructions, is available from the Integrated Public Use Microdata Series.
[src:alfred-village-new-york/1900-united-states-census] Statistician Frederick Ludwig Hoffman criticized the conduct of the census.
[src:alfred-village-new-york/1900-united-states-census] The original census enumeration sheets were microfilmed by the Census Bureau in the 1940s, after which the original sheets were destroyed.
[src:alfred-village-new-york/1900-united-states-census] Several organizations also host images of the microfilmed census online, and digital indices.
[src:alfred-village-new-york/1900-united-states-census] Microdata from the 1900 census are freely available through IPUMS.
[src:alfred-village-new-york/1900-united-states-census] Aggregate data for small areas, together with electronic boundary files, can be downloaded from the National Historical Geographic Information System.
[src:alfred-village-new-york/1900-united-states-census] Location of 50 largest cities by population in the United States in 1900, on a map of the modern United States.
[src:alfred-village-new-york/1910-united-states-census] The **1910 United States census**, conducted by the Census Bureau on April 15, 1910, determined the resident population of the United States to be 92,228,496, an increase of 21 percent over the 76,212,168 persons enumerated during the 1900 census.
[src:alfred-village-new-york/1910-united-states-census] The 1910 census switched from a portrait page orientation to a landscape orientation.
[src:alfred-village-new-york/1910-united-states-census] This was the last census in which Texas did not record any top 50 largest cities by population, despite being the 5th most populous state at the time.
[src:alfred-village-new-york/1910-united-states-census] It was also the first census in which all the top 50 largest cities had population over 100,000.
[src:alfred-village-new-york/1910-united-states-census] The 1910 census was the first to use metropolitan districts, the predecessor to modern metropolitan statistical areas, which were defined for all cities with at least 200,000 people.
[src:alfred-village-new-york/1910-united-states-census] Edward Dana Durand, then-head of the Bureau of Corporations, was appointed in 1909 to oversee the census. $14 million were allocated to conduct the census.
[src:alfred-village-new-york/1910-united-states-census] Full documentation for the 1910 census, including census forms and enumerator instructions, is available from the Integrated Public Use Microdata Series.
[src:alfred-village-new-york/1910-united-states-census] Number of dwelling house in order of visitation.
[src:alfred-village-new-york/1910-united-states-census] Number of family in order of visitation.
[src:alfred-village-new-york/1910-united-states-census] NAME of each person whose place of abode on April 15, 1910, was in this family.
[src:alfred-village-new-york/1910-united-states-census] Enter surname first, then the given name and middle initial, if any.
[src:alfred-village-new-york/1910-united-states-census] Include every person living on April 15, 1910.
[src:alfred-village-new-york/1910-united-states-census] Omit children born since April 15, 1910.
[src:alfred-village-new-york/1910-united-states-census] Relationship of this person to the head of the family.
[src:alfred-village-new-york/1910-united-states-census] Whether single, married, widowed, or divorced.
[src:alfred-village-new-york/1910-united-states-census] Mother of how many children: Number born.
[src:alfred-village-new-york/1910-united-states-census] Mother of how many children: Number now living.
[src:alfred-village-new-york/1910-united-states-census] Place of birth of each person and parents of each person enumerated.
