[src:alfred-village-new-york/1910-united-states-census] Place of birth of Father of this person.
[src:alfred-village-new-york/1910-united-states-census] Place of birth of Mother of this person.
[src:alfred-village-new-york/1910-united-states-census] Year of immigration to the United States.
[src:alfred-village-new-york/1910-united-states-census] Whether able to speak English; or, if not, give language spoken.
[src:alfred-village-new-york/1910-united-states-census] General nature of industry, business, or establishment in which this person works, as *cotton mill, dry goods store, farm*, etc.
[src:alfred-village-new-york/1910-united-states-census] Whether as employer, employee, or work on own account.
[src:alfred-village-new-york/1910-united-states-census] Number of weeks out of work during year 1909.
[src:alfred-village-new-york/1910-united-states-census] Attended school any time since September 1, 1909.
[src:alfred-village-new-york/1910-united-states-census] Whether a survivor of the Union or Confederate Army or Navy.
[src:alfred-village-new-york/1910-united-states-census] Location of 50 largest cities by population in the United States in 1910.
[src:alfred-village-new-york/1910-united-states-census] The original census enumeration sheets were microfilmed by the Census Bureau in the 1940s; after which the original sheets were destroyed.
[src:alfred-village-new-york/1910-united-states-census] Several organizations also host images of the microfilmed census online, along with digital indices.
[src:alfred-village-new-york/1910-united-states-census] Microdata from the 1910 census are freely available through the Integrated Public Use Microdata Series.
[src:alfred-village-new-york/1920-united-states-census] The **1920 United States census**, conducted by the Census Bureau during one month from January 5, 1920, determined the resident population of the United States to be 106,021,537, an increase of 15.0 percent over the 92,228,496 persons enumerated during the 1910 census.
[src:alfred-village-new-york/1920-united-states-census] The 1920 Census was determined for 1 January 1920.
[src:alfred-village-new-york/1920-united-states-census] The actual date of the enumeration appears on the heading of each page of the census schedule, but all responses were to reflect the individual's status as of 1 January, even if the status had changed between 1 January and the day of enumeration.
[src:alfred-village-new-york/1920-united-states-census] In 1929, Congress passed the Reapportionment Act of 1929 which provided for a permanent method of reapportionment and fixed the number of representatives at 435.
[src:alfred-village-new-york/1920-united-states-census] This was the first census in which the United States recorded a population of more than 100 million.
[src:alfred-village-new-york/1920-united-states-census] It was also the first census in which a state—New York—recorded a population of more than ten million.
[src:alfred-village-new-york/1920-united-states-census] This census also marked a significant population shift from rural to urban.
[src:alfred-village-new-york/1920-united-states-census] According to the Census Bureau, "Beginning in 1910, the minimum population threshold to be categorized as an urban place was set at 2,500.
[src:alfred-village-new-york/1920-united-states-census] 'Urban' was defined as including all territory, persons, and housing units within an incorporated area that met the population threshold.
[src:alfred-village-new-york/1920-united-states-census] Full documentation for the 1920 census, including census forms and enumerator instructions, is available from the Integrated Public Use Microdata Series.
[src:alfred-village-new-york/1920-united-states-census] Location of 50 largest cities by population in the United States in 1920.
[src:alfred-village-new-york/1920-united-states-census] Microdata from the 1920 census are freely available through the Integrated Public Use Microdata Series.
[src:alfred-village-new-york/1930-united-states-census] The **1930 United States census**, conducted by the Census Bureau one month from April 1, 1930, determined the resident population of the United States to be 122,775,046, an increase of 13.7 percent over the 106,021,537 persons enumerated during the 1920 census.
[src:alfred-village-new-york/1930-united-states-census] It was the first time the effects of suburban sprawl were recorded when, during the Roaring Twenties, a significant portion of the working population of New York City moved to New Jersey, aided by the George Washington Bridge which permitted quick transport from the state to Manhattan.
[src:alfred-village-new-york/1930-united-states-census] It was also the first in which a city in the Western United States (Los Angeles) reached a population of at least a million people.
[src:alfred-village-new-york/1930-united-states-census] Full documentation for the 1930 census, including census forms and enumerator instructions, is available from the Integrated Public Use Microdata Series.
[src:alfred-village-new-york/1930-united-states-census] The original census enumeration sheets were microfilmed by the Census Bureau in 1949, after which the original sheets were destroyed.
[src:alfred-village-new-york/1930-united-states-census] The microfilmed census is located on 2,667 rolls of microfilm, and available from the National Archives and Records Administration.
[src:alfred-village-new-york/1930-united-states-census] Microdata from the 1930 census are freely available through the Integrated Public Use Microdata Series.
[src:alfred-village-new-york/1930-united-states-census] Location of 50 largest cities by population in the United States in 1930.
[src:alfred-village-new-york/alfred-village-new-york] The village is home to both Alfred University and Alfred State College.
[src:alfred-village-new-york/alfred-village-new-york] In 2023, *The Washington Post* named it "the collegiest college town in America" due to its high ratio of students to non-students.
[src:alfred-village-new-york/alfred-village-new-york] Due in part to the New York State College of Ceramics, Alfred has become a hub for ceramic artists and ceramic engineers.
[src:alfred-village-new-york/alfred-village-new-york] The area around Alfred had historically been home to the Seneca tribe.
[src:alfred-village-new-york/alfred-village-new-york] In 1807, three Seventh Day Baptists, Clark Crandall, Nathan Green, and Edward Green, moved to the area with their families, becoming the first of many members of that sect to move to the village and surrounding region.
[src:alfred-village-new-york/alfred-village-new-york] Alfred's name has traditionally been attributed to Alfred the Great, however that has never been definitively verified.
[src:alfred-village-new-york/alfred-village-new-york] For much of its early history the village of Alfred was known as Alfred Centre.
[src:alfred-village-new-york/alfred-village-new-york] Alfred became home to an institution of higher education in 1832, when Alfred University was founded.
[src:alfred-village-new-york/alfred-village-new-york] The college was coeducational from its inception and tried to provide practical as well as liberal education for students.
[src:alfred-village-new-york/alfred-village-new-york] This university was initially considered the principal seat of higher learning supported by the Seventh Day Baptists although it was not directly supported by the denomination.
[src:alfred-village-new-york/alfred-village-new-york] The village was a hotbed of support for the abolition movement and during the American Civil War nearly 150 residents fought for the union.
[src:alfred-village-new-york/alfred-village-new-york] In 1888 the Celadon Terra Cotta Company was founded after the discovery of high-quality clay in the area.
[src:alfred-village-new-york/alfred-village-new-york] The company grew over the next decade to become a leading producer of roof tile and architectural terra cotta.
[src:alfred-village-new-york/alfred-village-new-york] The presence of this and the nearby Alfred Clay Company helped to establish Alfred as a ceramics hub, and led to the local university being selected as the home of the New York State College of Ceramics in 1900.
[src:alfred-village-new-york/alfred-village-new-york] The new college recruited British ceramicist Charles Fergus Binns as a director and professor.
[src:alfred-village-new-york/alfred-village-new-york] Binns was a proponent of the Arts and Crafts movement and considered it essential for a student of ceramics to understand both the artistic and technical aspects of their craft.
[src:alfred-village-new-york/alfred-village-new-york] Under his leadership the college grew into a leading institution of ceramic studies, eventually developing separate schools for ceramic art and ceramic engineering.
[src:alfred-village-new-york/alfred-village-new-york] As a result of the college's prominence, Alfred remained a hub for ceramics even after the burning of the Celadon Terra Cotta Company's local factory in 1909.
[src:alfred-village-new-york/alfred-village-new-york] A statutory agricultural school was formed at Alfred University in 1908, with a farm, livestock, and farm machinery for trade education.
[src:alfred-village-new-york/alfred-village-new-york] In 1937 a school of Engineering Technology was formed at this college, and in 1948 the entire college was spun off from Alfred University to form Alfred State College.
[src:alfred-village-new-york/alfred-village-new-york] From 1940 to 1957 the village was home to Glidden Pottery, a unique stoneware-bodied dinnerware with designs by founder Glidden Parker, Sergio Dello Strologo, Fong Chow, and others.
[src:alfred-village-new-york/alfred-village-new-york] These pieces were affordable for many, yet showcased unique midcentury modern styles and designs.
[src:alfred-village-new-york/alfred-village-new-york] They have become highly collectable in the years since the pottery's closing.
[src:alfred-village-new-york/alfred-village-new-york] On April 30, 1972, the village hosted the first Hot Dog Day, organized jointly by Alfred University and Alfred State College students.
[src:alfred-village-new-york/alfred-village-new-york] Alfred is home to numerous buildings and properties listed on the National Register of Historic Places: Alumni Hall, Fireman's Hall, Steinheim Castle and the Terra Cotta Building.
[src:alfred-village-new-york/alfred-village-new-york] Additionally, 55 properties in Alfred's downtown form the Alfred Village Historic District.
[src:alfred-village-new-york/alfred-village-new-york] Alfred is approximately located at 42.3° north latitude, 77.8° west longitude.
[src:alfred-village-new-york/alfred-village-new-york] According to the United States Census Bureau, the village has a total area of 1.2 square miles (3.1 km2), all land.
[src:alfred-village-new-york/alfred-village-new-york] A small stream, Kanakadea Creek, flows through the center of the village, then to the Canisteo River, part of the Susquehanna River watershed.
[src:alfred-village-new-york/alfred-village-new-york] The topography is steep hill country, part of the Allegheny Plateau, a physiographic region that is part of the Appalachian Mountains.
[src:alfred-village-new-york/alfred-village-new-york] Alfred is located in the hills of western New York along the Southern Tier.
[src:alfred-village-new-york/alfred-village-new-york] The layout of the valley is such that the lowest part contains the village, and upon the hills to the east and west are Alfred University and Alfred State College, respectively.
[src:alfred-village-new-york/alfred-village-new-york] The valley was originally called *Kanakadea* (or *Canakadea*, or other spellings) by Native Americans.
[src:alfred-village-new-york/alfred-village-new-york] The elevation of Alfred is about 1,700 feet (520 m) but rises to a high point of 2,355 feet (718 m) at the summit of Jericho Hill just south of the village.
[src:alfred-village-new-york/alfred-village-new-york] The hills greatly affect the weather in the region, which results in quick changes as well as different conditions in neighboring valleys.
[src:alfred-village-new-york/alfred-village-new-york] As of the census of 2000, there were 3,954 people, 530 households, and 169 families residing in the village.
[src:alfred-village-new-york/alfred-village-new-york] The population density was 3,352.5 inhabitants per square mile (1,294.4/km2).
[src:alfred-village-new-york/alfred-village-new-york] There were 576 housing units at an average density of 488.4 per square mile (188.6/km2).
[src:alfred-village-new-york/alfred-village-new-york] The racial makeup of the village was 90.21% White, 4.40% Black or African American, 0.33% Native American, 2.71% Asian, 0.03% Pacific Islander, 1.21% from other races, and 1.11% from two or more races.
[src:alfred-village-new-york/alfred-village-new-york] Hispanic or Latino of any race were 2.73% of the population.
[src:alfred-village-new-york/alfred-village-new-york] There were 530 households, out of which 12.3% had children under the age of 18 living with them, 26.0% were married couples living together, 4.2% had a female householder with no husband present, and 68.1% were non-families.
[src:alfred-village-new-york/alfred-village-new-york] 38.9% of all households were made up of individuals, and 10.6% had someone living alone who was 65 years of age or older.
[src:alfred-village-new-york/alfred-village-new-york] The average household size was 2.05 and the average family size was 2.73.
[src:alfred-village-new-york/alfred-village-new-york] In the village, the population was spread out, with 3.0% under the age of 18, 83.1% from 18 to 24, 5.9% from 25 to 44, 4.6% from 45 to 64, and 3.3% who were 65 years of age or older.
[src:alfred-village-new-york/alfred-village-new-york] For every 100 females, there were 144.8 males.
[src:alfred-village-new-york/alfred-village-new-york] For every 100 females age 18 and over, there were 147.2 males.
[src:alfred-village-new-york/alfred-village-new-york] The median income for a household in the village was $21,313, and the median income for a family was $70,694.
[src:alfred-village-new-york/alfred-village-new-york] Males had a median income of $15,750 versus $39,375 for females.
[src:alfred-village-new-york/alfred-village-new-york] The per capita income for the village was $8,224.
[src:alfred-village-new-york/alfred-village-new-york] About 2.0% of families and 37.7% of the population were below the poverty line, including none of those under age 18 and 2.8% of those age 65 or over.
